WEBVTT

00:01.710 --> 00:03.086
ANNIE:
Yes, Mr. Smith.

00:03.169 --> 00:04.337
{\an5}PHIL (over phone):
Annie, the test groups need
to be ready by Monday.

00:04.421 --> 00:06.756
{\an5}ANNIE: Yes, sir, of course.

00:04.421 --> 00:06.756
Do I need to find someone else?

00:06.840 --> 00:08.591
{\an5}ANNIE:
I was just pointing out
I've only been here two months

00:08.675 --> 00:09.968
and wanted to make sure
you were comfortable

00:10.051 --> 00:11.428
with me administrating
the tests.

00:11.511 --> 00:13.555
{\an5}PHIL:
This isn't rocket science.

00:13.638 --> 00:14.973
I'm glad to take it
off your plate.

00:15.056 --> 00:17.934
Bye, Annie.

00:18.017 --> 00:20.103
{\an6}DYLAN:
You know, you don't have
to agree to everything

00:20.186 --> 00:22.188
{\an5}Phil asks of you.

00:20.186 --> 00:22.188
(chuckles)

00:22.272 --> 00:24.482
Eh, it's no big deal.

00:24.566 --> 00:26.568
We're doing a trial
for that new medicated lip balm.

00:26.651 --> 00:28.278
I'm just organizing
the placebo group.

00:28.361 --> 00:29.821
You could try saying no
to the assignment.

00:29.904 --> 00:33.199
Mm. I feel weird saying no.

00:33.283 --> 00:36.411
I don't want them to think
I'm... I'm not a team player.

00:36.494 --> 00:37.412
I'll talk to Phil.

00:37.495 --> 00:38.705
{\an1}ANNIE:
Oh, no, you...

00:38.788 --> 00:39.956
You don't have to do that.

00:40.039 --> 00:41.416
{\an1}I'm on it.

00:43.042 --> 00:45.545
{\an3}Do you have plans to see
the Perseids tonight?

00:48.214 --> 00:50.258
{\an3}The meteor showers.
It's supposed to be, like,

00:50.341 --> 00:52.010
{\an3}the best light
show in 30 years.

00:53.052 --> 00:55.472
I've got to call the lab,

00:55.555 --> 00:57.432
reserve a conference room,

00:57.515 --> 00:59.100
I got to find subjects, and I...

00:59.184 --> 01:00.769
{\an3}Meteors,

01:00.852 --> 01:04.397
lobsters,

01:04.480 --> 01:05.857
corn...

01:05.940 --> 01:07.942
(laughs)
Uh...

01:10.195 --> 01:13.072
Okay.

01:13.156 --> 01:14.407
Yeah?

01:17.410 --> 01:18.328
I'll see you then.

01:18.411 --> 01:20.246
I'll see you then.

01:25.919 --> 01:29.005
("Whole Lotta Your Love"
by Lee Hurst playing)

01:29.088 --> 01:34.177
♪ You give me satisfaction ♪

01:34.260 --> 01:39.307
♪ And that's love indeed ♪

01:39.390 --> 01:41.184
♪ You give me
all the love you have... ♪

01:41.267 --> 01:42.352
{\an1}Thank you.

01:42.435 --> 01:44.562
No tannins.

01:44.646 --> 01:46.689
You remembered I'm allergic.

01:46.773 --> 01:49.651
(both chuckle)

01:49.734 --> 01:53.363
♪ I know you're not
holding out ♪

01:53.446 --> 01:55.073
♪ On me... ♪

01:53.446 --> 01:55.073
{\an3}Whoa.

01:55.156 --> 01:57.200
Did you see that?

01:57.283 --> 01:58.660
{\an3}Come here.

01:58.743 --> 02:01.204
♪ Whole lotta your love... ♪

02:01.287 --> 02:02.205
{\an3}Where?

02:01.287 --> 02:02.205
♪ I need a ♪

02:02.288 --> 02:03.706
{\an1}Uh...

02:03.790 --> 02:05.708
{\an5}♪ Whole lotta your love... ♪

02:03.790 --> 02:05.708
{\an3}Uh, may I?

02:05.792 --> 02:07.168
{\an3}There.

02:07.252 --> 02:09.378
Right up here.

02:09.461 --> 02:11.714
{\an3}See?

02:09.461 --> 02:11.714
Oh.

02:11.798 --> 02:13.633
(meteor whooshes)

02:15.093 --> 02:17.262
ANNIE:
One just hit the water tower.

02:19.764 --> 02:21.391
{\an3}Holy shit.

02:21.474 --> 02:24.769
{\an5}Was that a...?

02:21.474 --> 02:24.769
{\an3}Holy shit.

02:24.853 --> 02:26.729
Let's go check it out.

02:26.813 --> 02:29.607
DYLAN:
Whoa. Did you see that?

02:29.691 --> 02:31.401
Look.

02:31.484 --> 02:33.862
Come here.

02:33.945 --> 02:35.947
(insect trilling)

02:38.116 --> 02:40.994
(frog croaking)

02:41.077 --> 02:44.080
ANNIE:
Oh, man. Hey, be careful.

02:53.464 --> 02:56.426
DYLAN:
Ooh. Ooh.

02:56.509 --> 02:57.760
{\an3}Oh.

02:59.470 --> 03:02.432
{\an3}That's incredible.
Can you imagine?

03:02.515 --> 03:04.434
{\an3}Ten minutes ago, that
was in outer space.

03:04.517 --> 03:07.478
Can I hold it?

03:04.517 --> 03:07.478
{\an3}Uh...

03:07.562 --> 03:09.772
Uh, I don't know, it
might be radioactive.

03:09.856 --> 03:11.816
Oh, really?

03:09.856 --> 03:11.816
{\an3}Yeah.

03:11.900 --> 03:13.610
{\an4}Well, let's just try it and see
what... Let's see what...

03:11.900 --> 03:13.610
I don't know,

03:13.693 --> 03:15.278
it might have space germs.

03:15.361 --> 03:18.072
{\an5}(chuckles):
Oh, really? Space germs?

03:15.361 --> 03:18.072
Yeah.

03:18.156 --> 03:19.657
ANNIE:
Well, I think you now have them.

03:19.741 --> 03:21.492
DYLAN:
That's a good point.

03:21.576 --> 03:22.952
{\an5}ANNIE: Oh...

03:21.576 --> 03:22.952
All right, here,
maybe you should...

03:23.036 --> 03:25.288
{\an5}(Annie laughs)

03:23.036 --> 03:25.288
Here. Okay.

03:25.371 --> 03:26.748
Here, here-- no.

03:26.831 --> 03:28.124
{\an5}ANNIE:
You're gonna--
you can't share with me?

03:28.207 --> 03:29.918
DYLAN:
Well, we better go back inside.

03:30.001 --> 03:31.461
The martians might be coming.

03:31.544 --> 03:32.962
ANNIE:
Oh, stop.

03:35.048 --> 03:38.760
("Hello" by Lionel Richie
playing)

03:41.220 --> 03:45.600
This is really embarrassing,
but...

03:45.683 --> 03:48.269
I've been dying to ask you out.

03:48.353 --> 03:50.647
♪ Inside my mind... ♪

03:50.730 --> 03:52.899
{\an1}Really?

03:52.982 --> 03:56.152
You're really cute when
you're being a jobsworth.

03:56.235 --> 03:58.947
(laughs)
When I'm being a what?

03:59.030 --> 04:03.368
{\an3}The way you're...
super into your job.

04:03.451 --> 04:05.495
I guess that's me.

04:05.578 --> 04:07.372
{\an3}(quietly):
It's a compliment.

04:09.248 --> 04:11.709
♪ Hello ♪

04:11.793 --> 04:16.130
♪ Is it me you're looking for? ♪

04:16.214 --> 04:19.676
♪ I can see it in your eyes ♪

04:19.759 --> 04:24.305
♪ I can see it
in your smile ♪

04:24.389 --> 04:28.017
♪ You're all I've ever wanted ♪

04:28.101 --> 04:31.396
♪ And my arms are open wide ♪

04:31.479 --> 04:34.691
♪ 'Cause you know
just what to say... ♪

04:34.774 --> 04:37.860
{\an3}(grunts)
You know... I,

04:37.944 --> 04:39.862
just, uh...

04:39.946 --> 04:41.489
How can you leave now?

04:41.572 --> 04:43.491
I have a crazy day tomorrow.

04:43.574 --> 04:47.161
{\an3}Aren't you
feeling it, too?

04:47.245 --> 04:49.914
Watching the sky tonight,
we experienced something.

04:51.499 --> 04:56.337
Something literally... cosmic.

04:56.421 --> 04:59.340
{\an3}I mean,

04:59.424 --> 05:02.927
to me, it feels...

05:03.011 --> 05:05.221
like magic.

05:05.304 --> 05:06.639
{\an1}(exhales):
Oh...

05:08.433 --> 05:11.811
{\an1}This... This really
have been nice, but...

05:11.894 --> 05:14.897
I really like you, Annie.

05:14.981 --> 05:16.733
I like you, too, Dylan.

05:16.816 --> 05:19.235
{\an1}I-I, uh...

05:19.318 --> 05:23.614
♪ Or is someone loving you? ♪

05:23.698 --> 05:26.534
♪ Tell me how to win
your heart ♪

05:26.617 --> 05:29.245
♪ For I haven't got a clue... ♪

05:29.328 --> 05:31.539
{\an1}(chuckles)
I really can't.

05:31.622 --> 05:33.624
I have work to finish.

05:33.708 --> 05:36.419
{\an1}And, you know, I mean, you know
me, I'm a, I'm a jobsworth.

05:36.502 --> 05:38.588
{\an4}I, I...

05:36.502 --> 05:38.588
We're having such a good time.

05:38.671 --> 05:40.048
Uh, you know what?

05:40.131 --> 05:42.258
(clears throat)

05:42.341 --> 05:46.095
Uh, this is, this is awesome.

05:46.179 --> 05:48.264
{\an1}And thanks so much
for the great night, but I...

05:48.347 --> 05:50.725
I-I really do need to get home.

05:50.808 --> 05:52.727
So, that's it?

05:52.810 --> 05:54.228
You don't want to?

05:54.312 --> 05:56.230
{\an3}What?

05:56.314 --> 05:58.858
{\an3}Y-You're
not into it?

05:58.941 --> 06:01.402
{\an5}I'll do you first.

05:58.941 --> 06:01.402
Um... I'm gonna head out.

06:03.946 --> 06:05.698
W-Wait, what did I do wrong?

06:07.075 --> 06:09.452
(chuckles): Nothing.
Y-You did nothing wrong.

06:09.535 --> 06:10.620
Wait.

06:12.538 --> 06:15.625
A-Are you thinking
I'm trying to fuck you?

06:16.876 --> 06:19.921
{\an3}Right now?

06:20.004 --> 06:21.923
Um...

06:22.006 --> 06:25.176
W-Well, okay... No? But I-I...

06:25.259 --> 06:27.220
{\an3}Well, you're
acting like I am.

06:27.303 --> 06:30.473
Dylan, I'm, I'm, I'm not,
I'm-I'm really not.

06:30.556 --> 06:31.849
{\an1}Ow.

06:30.556 --> 06:31.849
That kind of hurts.

06:31.933 --> 06:34.435
D-Dylan, stop it. I...

06:34.519 --> 06:36.646
Everything's cool. I need,
I-I need you to listen to me.

06:36.729 --> 06:40.650
I... I really like you,
and, look,

06:40.733 --> 06:42.944
{\an1}we work together.
I-I want to see you again.

06:43.027 --> 06:45.780
It's just, you-- I... uh...

06:45.863 --> 06:49.742
{\an1}hey, you know,
what's, what's the rush?

06:54.539 --> 06:56.207
Yeah. I'm sorry.

06:56.290 --> 06:58.835
{\an3}You're right,
I'm sorry.

06:58.918 --> 07:00.878
It's totally cool.

07:00.962 --> 07:02.505
{\an3}Uh...

07:03.923 --> 07:06.843
Thank you for coming over.

07:06.926 --> 07:09.178
And I will see you tomorrow.

07:09.262 --> 07:10.555
(laughs):
Okay.

07:10.638 --> 07:13.516
Thanks for everything. Bye.

07:13.599 --> 07:16.144
(door opens)

07:16.227 --> 07:18.604
(door closes)

07:24.944 --> 07:26.988
(Dylan screaming)

07:44.922 --> 07:47.175
Meet Annie Miller.

07:47.258 --> 07:49.677
Annie has always seen
the world as a place

07:49.760 --> 07:53.514
where she could maintain control
if she just played by the rules.

07:53.598 --> 07:56.726
But tonight marks
the beginning of a change,

07:56.809 --> 08:01.898
both in her and in the idyllic
town she's always called home.

08:01.981 --> 08:04.108
On the eve
of her sister's birthday,

08:04.192 --> 08:06.235
Annie will be forced
to contend with an event

08:06.319 --> 08:08.029
well out of her control,

08:08.112 --> 08:11.949
and a simmering violence
about to boil over...

08:12.033 --> 08:15.328
into The Twilight Zone.

08:17.538 --> 08:19.081
<i>(The Twilight Zone</i> theme
playing)

08:19.165 --> 08:20.750
NARRATOR: <i> You're traveling</i>
<i>through another dimension,</i>

08:20.833 --> 08:24.253
<i>a dimension not only of</i>
<i>sight and sound but of mind.</i>

08:24.337 --> 08:27.465
<i>It is the middle ground</i>
<i>between light and shadow,</i>

08:27.548 --> 08:30.259
<i>between science</i>
<i>and superstition.</i>

08:30.343 --> 08:32.803
{\an8}<i>And it lies between</i>
<i>the pit of one's fears</i>

08:32.886 --> 08:35.640
{\an8}<i>and the summit</i>
<i>of one's knowledge.</i>

08:35.722 --> 08:38.893
<i>You are now traveling through</i>
<i>a dimension of imagination.</i>

08:38.976 --> 08:42.813
<i>You've just crossed over</i>
<i>into The Twilight Zone.</i>

08:47.026 --> 08:49.612
{\an8}DJ (over radio): Only hours
after the meteor shower,

08:49.695 --> 08:51.614
{\an8}the little red rocks
have already become

08:51.697 --> 08:54.617
{\an8}sought-after memorabilia
here in the town of Newbury.

08:54.700 --> 08:56.994
{\an8}We're already counting
several public and private

08:57.078 --> 08:59.413
{\an8}Facebook pages dedicated
to enthusiasts

08:59.497 --> 09:01.999
{\an8}showing off their
little pieces of history.

09:02.083 --> 09:03.960
{\an8}And of course
the celestial visitors

09:04.043 --> 09:06.963
{\an8}have sparked
more than a few superstitions.

09:07.046 --> 09:09.799
{\an8}Many people are organizing
meteor shower celebrations.

09:09.882 --> 09:11.801
{\an8}Some local stores are jumping
on the bandwagon

09:11.884 --> 09:15.680
{\an8}by imprinting T-shirts, coffee
mugs, and even telescopes.

09:15.763 --> 09:18.599
{\an8}And of course we have a report
from a local hospital

09:18.683 --> 09:20.685
{\an8}of a baby being born
during the shower.

09:20.768 --> 09:22.979
{\an8}They would like to celebrate
the birth of their child by...

09:23.062 --> 09:24.814
{\an8}(continues indistinctly)

09:27.692 --> 09:29.986
{\an8}(indistinct chatter)

09:30.069 --> 09:32.071
{\an8}(exhales)

09:42.540 --> 09:44.542
{\an8}♪ ♪

09:50.589 --> 09:52.633
{\an8}Morning, Annie.

09:54.260 --> 09:56.429
{\an7}We all set
for the test group on Monday?

09:56.512 --> 09:58.014
{\an8}Uh, yes, sir. All set.

09:58.097 --> 10:01.058
{\an8}I spoke to Dylan this morning.
I want you to brief him,

10:01.142 --> 10:03.394
{\an8}and I'll have him
take it from here.

10:03.477 --> 10:06.188
{\an8}Dylan? Oh, I'd hate
to trouble him.

10:06.272 --> 10:08.733
{\an8}I thought he was tied up
with Perry on the launch.

10:08.816 --> 10:09.984
{\an8}I'm pretty sure I can handle it.

10:10.067 --> 10:12.361
{\an8}Well, I'm sure, too, Annie,
but there are protocols here.

10:12.445 --> 10:15.197
{\an8}Annie, protocols
are the methods

10:15.281 --> 10:16.741
{\an8}we use here.

10:16.824 --> 10:19.410
{\an8}Dylan is point on managing
laboratory analysis

10:19.493 --> 10:21.162
{\an8}for the testing
marketing group.

10:21.245 --> 10:23.039
{\an8}Plus, he's one of the best
here at the company, Annie.

10:23.122 --> 10:26.167
{\an8}Stick with him,
do as he does,

10:26.250 --> 10:27.668
{\an8}and you'll move up fast here.

10:27.752 --> 10:28.669
{\an8}Huh?

10:28.753 --> 10:30.546
{\an8}So, uh,

10:30.629 --> 10:32.048
{\an7}since that's
off your plate,

10:32.131 --> 10:33.924
{\an8}looks like Olivia and I
will see you tonight

10:34.008 --> 10:36.469
{\an8}at your sister's
birthday dinner.

10:54.779 --> 10:57.782
{\an8}And now, warrior.

11:09.126 --> 11:10.086
(bell rings)

11:10.169 --> 11:11.712
Look, I told you,
I had my account

11:11.796 --> 11:14.423
{\an3}under my ex-wife's
address.

11:14.507 --> 11:16.801
{\an1}I just need you to get
the papers out of there, okay?

11:16.884 --> 11:18.969
N-N-No, you listen.

11:21.347 --> 11:23.724
{\an6}(banging)

11:21.347 --> 11:23.724
(man grunting)

11:27.520 --> 11:29.772
(horn honks)

11:27.520 --> 11:29.772
{\an1}Lady,

11:29.855 --> 11:31.607
can you move?

11:31.690 --> 11:33.943
(horn honking)

11:34.026 --> 11:36.654
(panting)

11:57.883 --> 11:59.802
{\an1}(gasps)

11:59.885 --> 12:01.887
{\an1}(sighs)

12:03.347 --> 12:05.599
{\an3}Yo, Auntie A,
were you sleeping?

12:05.683 --> 12:06.809
'Cause that'd be weird.

12:06.892 --> 12:09.687
Um, no, I...

12:09.770 --> 12:11.814
{\an1}I was taking a moment,
that's it.

12:11.897 --> 12:13.149
{\an3}Right.

12:16.610 --> 12:18.320
Oh, God, you're taller.

12:18.404 --> 12:19.363
{\an3}Yep.

12:19.447 --> 12:22.116
{\an1}How is it
that you're taller?

12:22.199 --> 12:25.494
Well, I'm growing at a
normal rate, I guess,

12:25.578 --> 12:28.539
but you don't, uh,
see me very often.

12:28.622 --> 12:30.499
That's how that works.

12:30.583 --> 12:31.792
Hey, how crazy
was last night?

12:31.876 --> 12:34.462
There were meteors
all over the place.

12:34.545 --> 12:36.213
Kids at school are
obsessed with them.

12:36.297 --> 12:37.339
Yeah.

12:37.423 --> 12:41.677
A couple landed behind
this guy's house. It was crazy.

12:41.760 --> 12:43.846
"This guy"?

12:43.929 --> 12:47.475
{\an1}You went on
a little date, huh?

12:47.558 --> 12:50.019
What's wrong? What happened?

12:51.854 --> 12:55.566
Uh... he just, uh,

12:55.649 --> 12:57.651
he just got weird on me.

12:57.735 --> 12:59.487
That sucks.

12:59.570 --> 13:01.780
If only there was a way to
figure out which, which guys

13:01.864 --> 13:04.116
were gonna be assholes,
you know?

13:04.200 --> 13:06.577
(sighs)
I wish I could kick his ass.

13:06.660 --> 13:09.246
{\an3}(chuckles) And what good
would that do?

13:09.330 --> 13:11.165
Well, you know...

13:11.248 --> 13:13.042
Why do guys always
want to kick ass?

13:13.125 --> 13:14.627
'Cause we're dudes!

13:14.710 --> 13:16.670
{\an1}Thank you, Phil,
Olivia, I love it.

13:16.754 --> 13:18.339
{\an4}Cole, put this in
your bathroom.

13:16.754 --> 13:18.339
You're welcome.

13:18.422 --> 13:19.381
Yes, yes.

13:19.465 --> 13:21.509
{\an5}Those are awesome.

13:19.465 --> 13:21.509
(chuckles)

13:21.592 --> 13:25.387
Okay, and, oh,
what's next?

13:25.471 --> 13:26.847
{\an3}Oh, what on earth
could this be?

13:26.931 --> 13:28.182
{\an5}OLIVIA: No idea.

13:26.931 --> 13:28.182
I don't, I don't have any...

13:28.265 --> 13:30.017
{\an5}It's a James Patterson novel.

13:28.265 --> 13:30.017
Could we...?

13:30.100 --> 13:32.019
(laughter)

13:32.102 --> 13:34.188
{\an3}Um, the-the receipt's
on the bottom.

13:34.271 --> 13:36.232
I'm sure there's a fancier
skillet you would want.

13:36.315 --> 13:38.234
What is that?
That's a nine-inch, right?

13:38.317 --> 13:39.777
{\an1}I love it, Annie!
Thank you.

13:39.860 --> 13:41.570
{\an5}We need this. Mike.

13:39.860 --> 13:41.570
{\an1}Yeah.
That's a good one.

13:41.654 --> 13:43.531
{\an1}I could've used this bad boy
for that eggplant terrine,

13:43.614 --> 13:44.907
by the way.

13:43.614 --> 13:44.907
{\an3}Definitely.

13:44.990 --> 13:46.075
First time we had that
was in Paris, right?

13:46.158 --> 13:47.743
He wouldn't-- Sorry.

13:47.826 --> 13:49.411
{\an5}You go. No.

13:47.826 --> 13:49.411
{\an3}Do you want...?
You can tell it, I don't care.

13:49.495 --> 13:50.704
No. Love you.

13:49.495 --> 13:50.704
{\an3}I love you.

13:50.788 --> 13:53.749
{\an3}Uh, so, I go into the kitchen to
ask the chef for the recipe...

13:53.832 --> 13:54.750
{\an5}He means in French.

13:53.832 --> 13:54.750
(laughs): Right.

13:54.833 --> 13:56.252
Just get that in.

13:56.335 --> 13:59.755
But my-my-my French
is, uh-uh,<i> très mauvais.</i>

13:59.838 --> 14:01.715
{\an3}So-so, the chef
answered in English.

14:01.799 --> 14:04.093
{\an5}(laughter)

14:01.799 --> 14:04.093
Just to make a point.

14:04.176 --> 14:06.387
You should've had Martha ask.
Her French is amazing.

14:06.470 --> 14:08.597
